{{Infobox cricketer | name = | image = | country = Ireland | fullname = Donald Montague McVeagh Pratt | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1935|7|9|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Dublin]], [[Leinster]], Ireland | death_date = | death_place = | nickname = | family = [[George McVeagh]] (uncle) | batting = Left-handed | bowling = | role = | club1 = [[Ireland cricket team|Ireland]] | year1 = 1963&ndash;1966 | columns = 1 | column1 = [[First-class cricket|First-class]] | matches1 = 6 | runs1 = 171 | bat avg1 = 14.25 | 100s/50s1 = –/2 | top score1 = 58 | deliveries1 = 0 | wickets1 = – | bowl avg1 = – | fivefor1 = – | tenfor1 = – | best bowling1 = – | catches/stumpings1 = –/– | date = 26 October | year = 2018 | source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/ireland/content/player/24497.html Cricinfo }}
'''Donald Montague McVeagh Pratt''' (born 9 July 1935) is an [[Irish people|Irish]] businessman and former first-class [[cricket]]er.
Born at [[Dublin]], Pratt was educated in the city at [[Sandford Park School]] and [[St Columba's College, Dublin|St Columba's College]].<ref name="CE">{{cite web|url=https://www.cricketeurope.com/IRELAND/PLAYERS/498/index.shtml |title=Donald Montague McVeagh Pratt |publisher=CricketEurope |accessdate=2018-10-26}}</ref> He later studied at the [[University of Dublin]], where he played cricket for [[Dublin University Cricket Club]].<ref name="CE"/> After completing his studies, Pratt moved into the legal profession as a solicitor.<ref name="CE"/> Playing his club cricket in Dublin for [[Phoenix Cricket Club|Phoenix]],<ref name="CE"/> he made his debut in [[first-class cricket]] for [[Ireland cricket team|Ireland]] against [[Scotland cricket team|Scotland]] at [[Beechgrove|Derry]] in 1963.<ref name="FCM">{{cite web|url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/26/26878/First-Class_Matches.html |title=First-Class Matches played by Donald Pratt |publisher=CricketEurope |accessdate=2018-10-26}}</ref> He played five further first-class matches for Ireland, appearing against the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] (MCC) in 1964, the touring [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealanders]], Scotland, and [[Hampshire County Cricket Club|Hampshire]] in 1965, and the MCC in 1966.<ref name="FCM"/> He scored 171 run in these six matches, [[batting average|averaging]] 14.25.<ref name="FCB">{{cite web|url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/26/26878/f_Batting_by_Team.html |title=First-class Batting and Fielding For Each Team by Donald Pratt |publisher=CricketEurope |accessdate=2018-10-26}}</ref> He had just two innings of note where he passed fifty,<ref name="FCB"/> with a highest score of 58 against the New Zealanders at [[Ormeau Cricket Ground|Belfast]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/27/27629.html |title=Ireland v New Zealanders, 1965 |publisher=CricketEurope |accessdate=2018-10-26}}</ref><ref name="CE"/> Pratt was also a noted [[Squash (sport)|squash]] player, winning the Irish Squash Championship for ten years in a row.<ref name="NEWS">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/business/donald-pratt-26417691.html|title=Donald Pratt|date=2006-10-22|work=[[Irish Independent]]|accessdate=2018-10-26}}</ref> He stopped working as a solicitor in 1974, when he and his wife purchased [[Avoca Handweavers]], a [[County Wicklow]] business dating back to 1723.<ref name="NEWS"/> By 2006, the company had eight stores in Ireland and one in the United States, and employed 475 people.<ref name="NEWS"/>
