'''Richard More O'Ferrall''' (1797 – 27 October 1880) was an [[Irish people|Irish]] politician, a high level British government official and a [[Governor of Malta]].

==Career==
Richard More O'Ferrall was born in Moyvalley, [[County Kildare]], Ireland, to the prestigious House of More O'Ferrall. He was the eldest son of [[Major (British Army)|Major]] Ambrose O'Ferrall (1752–1835) and his first wife, Anne Bagot.<ref name=odnb>[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/20565?docPos=1 Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]</ref> He was elected to the [[British House of Commons]] in 1832, and represented the Constituencies of [[County Kildare]] from 10 December 1832 to 29 July 1847, and subsequently [[Longford]] from 21 April 1851 to 7 July 1852 and Kildare again from 28 April 1859 to 11 July 1865. 

Under the [[Whigs (British political party)|Whig administration]] of [[William Lamb, 2nd Viscount Melbourne|Lord Melbourne]], He entered the Government as a [[Lords Commissioners of the Treasury|Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]] in 1835, and remained so until 1837.

On 28 September 1839, More O'Ferrall married Matilda (died 1882), the second daughter of [[Thomas Southwell, 3rd Viscount Southwell|The 3rd Viscount Southwell]], [[Order of St. Patrick|KP]].<ref name=loney>{{cite web|url=http://www.pdavis.nl/ShowBiog.php?id=69|title=Biography of  Richard More O'Ferrall|work=pdavis.nl}}</ref> The couple had a son, [[Ambrose More O'Ferrall|Ambrose]], and a daughter, Maria Anne. 

A week after his marriage, on 4 October 1839, More O'Ferrall was appointed to the Government as First Secretary of the [[Royal Navy]], a post he retained until June 1841, when he briefly became Secretary to the Treasury. In October 1847 he became [[Governor of Malta]].<ref name=loney/> On 12 September 1851 More O'Ferrall resigned as governor, refusing to serve under [[Lord John Russell]], whose [[Ecclesiastical Titles Act]] was designed to prevent a restoration of the Roman Catholic hierarchy in England.<ref name=odnb/>

==Death==
More O'Ferrall died in 1880	in [[Dún Laoghaire|Kingstown]] (present-day Dún Laoghaire), [[County Dublin]].

